<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
This taxon occurs in brackish and fresh water habitats, commonly found in estuaries of large rivers, also surviving in inland waters with high conductivity, this is a halophilic species. It has considerable abundance in epiphytic, benthic hard waters with relatively high electrical conductivity. Distributed and more abundant in warm-temperate and tropical waters, being mesohalobic, from alkalibiontic to alkaliphilic indicator, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="β-mesosaprobic">β-mesosaprobic</normalizedToken>
, and eutraphentic (
<bibRefCitation author="El-Awamri, AF" journalOrPublisher="Australian Journal of Basic and Applied Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="22 - 29" refId="B25" refString="El-Awamri, AF, 2008. Studies on the Morphology of Different Valve Types of the Centric Diatom Species Pleurosira laevis (Ehr.) Compere. Australian Journal of Basic and Applied Sciences 2 (1): 22 - 29" title="Studies on the Morphology of Different Valve Types of the Centric Diatom Species Pleurosira laevis (Ehr.) Compere." volume="2" year="2008">El-Awamri 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
Valves were found in benthic samples in the Mykolaiv city of the Southern Bug River and downriver (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Species composition of centric diatoms at the investigated sites near Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River in the year 2017 (2013 added for station 2)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" tableUuid="DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677">1</tableCitation>
). For Ukrainian territory it was recorded for estuaries of the Black Sea, also reported for the Southern Bug River (
<bibRefCitation author="Tsarenko, PM" journalOrPublisher="Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B127" refString="Tsarenko, PM, Wasser, SP, Nevo, E, 2009. Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A.R.A. Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" title="Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A. R. A." year="2009">Tsarenko et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pleurosira laevis" order="Triceratiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="laevis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Pleurosira laevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite cosmopolitan, distributed in the Boreal, near coasts of Europe (Czech Republic, Finland, Germany, Romania, Russia, Sweden, Ukraine), Asia (Korea, Turkey), South America (Brazil), Africa (Egypt), Hawaiian Islands; Azov, Black and Marmora Seas (
<bibRefCitation author="Tsarenko, PM" journalOrPublisher="Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B127" refString="Tsarenko, PM, Wasser, SP, Nevo, E, 2009. Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A.R.A. Gantner Verlag, Ruggell" title="Algae of Ukraine: diversity, nomenclature, taxonomy, ecology and geography. Vol. 2. Bacillariophyta. A. R. A." year="2009">Tsarenko et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/nova_hedwigia/2016/0384" author="Park, SY" journalOrPublisher="Nova Hedwigia" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="151 - 166" refId="B101" refString="Park, SY, Choi, JS, Kim, JH, Kim, HS, 2017b. Morphology and physico-ecology of two rare freshwater epilithic diatoms: Hydrosera whampoensis and Pleurosira laevis. Nova Hedwigia 105 (1-2): 151 - 166, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/nova_hedwigia/2016/0384" title="Morphology and physico-ecology of two rare freshwater epilithic diatoms: Hydrosera whampoensis and Pleurosira laevis." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/nova_hedwigia/2016/0384" volume="105" year="2017 b">Park et al. 2017b</bibRefCitation>
). For Europe this taxon is considered an invasive species (
<bibRefCitation author="Handbook of alien species in Europe DAISIE" journalOrPublisher="Diatom Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B52" refString="Handbook of alien species in Europe DAISIE, 2009. Invading nature - Springer series in invasion ecology 3 (2nd ed.). New York, 399 pp." title="Invading nature - Springer series in invasion ecology 3 (2 nd ed.). New York, 399 pp." year="2009">Handbook of alien species in Europe DAISIE 2009</bibRefCitation>
). An upstream colonisation of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pleurosira laevis" order="Triceratiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="laevis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Pleurosira laevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with help of different vectors for the River Labe was discussed by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3372/cediatom.108" author="Frankova-Kozakova, M" editor="Kusber, W-H" journalOrPublisher="Berlin-Dahlem, 23 - 25 March 2007. Berlin: Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin-Dahlem, Freie Universitaet Berlin" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="39 - 44" refId="B31" refString="Frankova-Kozakova, M, Marvan, P, Geris, R, 2007. Halophilous diatoms in Czech running waters: Pleurosira laevis and Bacillaria paxillifera. In: Kusber, W-H, Jahn, R, Eds., Proceedings of the 1st Central European Diatom Meeting 2007. Berlin-Dahlem, 23-25 March 2007. Berlin: Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin-Dahlem, Freie Universitaet Berlin: 39 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3372/cediatom.108" title="Halophilous diatoms in Czech running waters: Pleurosira laevis and Bacillaria paxillifera." url="https://doi.org/10.3372/cediatom.108" volumeTitle="Proceedings of the 1 st Central European Diatom Meeting 2007." year="2007">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Fránková-Kozáková">Frankova-Kozakova</normalizedToken>
et al. (2007)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
